<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n16015e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n16" href="#n16015e">N16 (VI.D.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n16all.htm#n16015e"> 15(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Poison gas / lachrymatory gas</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Chemical warfare had been so far foreseen by statesmen that in 1907 the signatories of the Hague Conference agreed to renounce the use of projectiles the sole object of which was the diffusion of asphyxiating or harmful gases. They were thus debarred from using <mark>lachrymatory gas</mark>, the most humane weapon ever invented; but permitted to discharge gas from cylinders on the ground, an exceedingly cruel practice. This regulation was well meant, but the path to August, 1914, was paved with good intentions. In 1914 none of the great powers had made any preparation for <mark>poison-gas</mark> warfare, and it was not till April 22nd, 1915, more than eight months after the beginning of the war, that the Germans began its use <small> J.B.S. Haldane, <a name="CHEM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CHEM"><cite title="source">Callinicus</cite></a> (1925) 7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c02137e" href="c02all.htm#c02137e">VI.C.02:137(e)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
